<h1 id="1.-Introduction">1. Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.-Introduction">&#182;</a></h1><p>For this project we were asked to select a dataset and using the data answer a question of our choosing. I selected the Titanic Data Set which looks at the characteristics of a sample of the passengers on the Titanic, including whether they survived or not, gender, age, siblings / spouses, parents and children, fare (cost of ticket), embarkation port.</p>
<p>After looking at the contents of the dataset, I thought it would be interesting to look at the following questions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Which gender had a better chance of survival?</li>
<li>Which social class had a better chance of survival?</li>
<li>Which age group had a better chance of survival?</li>
</ul>
<h1 id="2.-Setting-up-report">2. Setting up report<a class="anchor-link" href="#2.-Setting-up-report">&#182;</a></h1><p>In order to analyse and report on the data, I have choosen to use ipython notebook, along with the numpy, pandas, matplotlib.pyplot and seaborn python modules.
In order to use these modules they needed to be imported into the notebook first as per below.</p>
</div>
</div>

<h2 id="4.5-Mapping-data-(values-to-descriptions)">4.5 Mapping data (values to descriptions)<a class="anchor-link" href="#4.5-Mapping-data-(values-to-descriptions)">&#182;</a></h2><p>In order to intrepret the data easier the following fields need to be modified:</p>
<ul>
<li>Survived - changed to boolean (1 = True, 0 = False)</li>
<li>Pclass - changed to Socio-Economic status (1st - Upper Class, 2nd - Middle Class, 3rd - Lower Class)</li>
<li>Embarked - changed to name of embarkation port (C = Cherbourg; Q = Queenstown; S = Southampton)</li>
</ul>
<p>I will also add a Family Size column so that I can compare the size of families with the number of survivors.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h2 id="5.2-Which-gender-had-a-better-chance-of-survival?">5.2 Which gender had a better chance of survival?<a class="anchor-link" href="#5.2-Which-gender-had-a-better-chance-of-survival?">&#182;</a></h2><p>In order to answer this question we need to look at how many males and females were on board and which gender had the highest survival rate.</p>

<p>HA = Gender does impact the chances of survivabily</p>

<h1 id="6.-Conclusion">6. Conclusion<a class="anchor-link" href="#6.-Conclusion">&#182;</a></h1><h3 id="6.1-Limitations-of-dataset">6.1 Limitations of dataset<a class="anchor-link" href="#6.1-Limitations-of-dataset">&#182;</a></h3><p>The are a number of limitations with the Titanic Dataset, which are caused by:</p>
<ul>
<li>missing data</li>
<li>only been a sample of the data</li>
</ul>
<p>The missing data and size of the sample could skew the results for example the missing ages.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[148]:</div>

</pre></div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The above shows that there were 53 ages missing for females and 124 ages missing for males. I had a choice with how to handle the missing ages each with their pros and cons.</p>
<ul>
<li>delete the rows with the missing ages - this would limit the accuracy of the analysis of the gender and class, however the accuracy of the analysis of the Age factor would be more accurate</li>
<li>generate ages based on the mean of ages - this could skew the results of the age analysis. In section 4.2, I choose this option, however I based the ages on the average for the Gender and Class.</li>
</ul>
<p>The size of the sample data could also impact the results as we don't know if this is a random sample or if the selection of the data is biased or unbiased.</p>
</div>
</div>

<h2 id="6.2-Other-variables">6.2 Other variables<a class="anchor-link" href="#6.2-Other-variables">&#182;</a></h2><p>As with most datasets the more information we have the better it can be analysed. I believe that we could add the following variables:</p>
<ul>
<li>passenger or crew - the current dataset doesn't distingush between passenger or crew, however from history we know that a mixture of both survived.</li>
<li>life boat number - the reason why there were so many fatalities on board the Titanic was due to there not been enough lifeboats. I believe that if we knew the lifeboat number and the capacity of a lifeboat we could determine if it was possible for more people to survive</li>
</ul>
